 november 1745","1738":"1738","1735":"1735","Evangelisch,Freckenfeld,Pfalz,Bavaria":"Pfalz, Bayern, Duitsland"},"en":{"–":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1728–1792":"1728–1792","1730–Female":"1730–Deceased","1735–Male":"1735–Deceased","1738–Male":"1738–Deceased","1745–Female":"1745–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1745":"1745","07 JUL 1730":"7 July 1730","19 JUL 1738":"19 July 1738","1730":"1730","09 NOV 1735":"9 November 1735","1792":"1792","1728":"1728","23 NOV 1745":"23 November 1745","1738":"1738","1735":"1735","Evangelisch,Freckenfeld,Pfalz,Bavaria":"Palatinate, Bavaria, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Nagel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Heinz, Hans, Otto, Kurt, Armin, Franz, Fritz, Udo, Wilhelm, Aloys.","German, Dutch, Scandinavian, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German, Middle Dutch <i>nagel</i>, German <i>Nagel</i> ‘nail’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a maker of nails. Compare   Nail  .","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Nahł</b>, <b>Nagł</b>, <b>Nahły</b>, and <b>Nagły</b>: nickname from Upper Sorbian <i>nahły</i>, Lower Sorbian <i>nagły</i> ‘quick’, also ‘hot-tempered’."],"variants":[{"name":"Nogle","meanings":["Possibly an altered form of German   Nagel   1."]},{"name":"Nail","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>naile</i>, <i>nayle</i> ‘nail’ (from Old English <i>nægel</i>), which may, as in modern English, have the senses ‘metal spike, wooden peg’or ‘fingernail, toenail’. Applied as a metonymic occupational name for a maker of nails.","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Nagel   ‘nail’.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Nahilo</i>, based on the element <i>nah</i> ‘sufficient, adequate’."]},{"name":"Naegele","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Alois, Bernhard, Erwin, Heinz, Hilde, Manfred, Matthias, Wolfgang.","South German (<b>Nägele</b>): variant of   Nagel  . Compare   Nagele  ."]},{"name":"Naegeli","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Markus, Otto, Wolfgang.","Swiss German (<b>Nägeli</b>): variant of   Nagel  ."]},{"name":"Naugle","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Nagel  ."]},{"name":"Negley","meanings":["Americanized form of Swiss German <b>Naegeli</b> or <b>Nägeli</b>, variants of   Nagel  . Compare   Nagley  ."]},{"name":"Nagele","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Jutta, Erwin, Rainer, Siegfried.","South German (<b>Nägele</b>): variant of   Nagel  . Compare   Naegele  ."]},{"name":"Noggle","meanings":["Possibly an altered form of German <b>Nöggel</b>, a variant of <b>Nöckel</b>, a South German topographic name from <i>Nock</i> ‘hill, peak, rock’, or of   Nagel   1. See   Nock  ."]}]},{"name":"Jacob","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, from Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>. This was borne by perhaps the most important of all the patriarchs in the Book of Genesis. Jacob was the father of twelve sons, who gave their names to the twelve tribes of Israel. He was the son of Isaac and Rebecca and twin brother of Esau. According to the story in Genesis, he was the cunning younger twin, who persuaded his brother Esau to part with his right to his inheritance in exchange for a bowl of soup (‘a mess of pottage’). Later, he tricked his blind and dying father into blessing him in place of Esau. The derivation of the name has been much discussed. It is traditionally explained as being derived from Hebrew <i>akev</i> ‘heel’ and to have meant ‘heel grabber’, because when Jacob was born ‘his hand took hold of Esau's heel’ (Genesis 25:26). This is interpreted later in the Bible as ‘supplanter’ Esau himself remarks, ‘Is he not rightly named Jacob? for he has supplanted me these two times’ (Genesis 27:36). <i>Jacob</i> is especially common as a Jewish given name, although it also became very 